title: CUDA: Enable parallel compilation
body:
This PR enables parallel compilation for CUDA. The already existing `--parallel <0-n>` option is passed on to nvcc as `--threads <0-n>`.

This feature is available starting with CUDA 11.3: https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-compiler-driver-nvcc/index.html#options-for-guiding-compiler-driver-threads

**Motivation and Context**
- This option cuts down the compilation time quite heavily when compiling for multiple architectures. On my machine, I am seeing around 25-50% faster build times when building for `CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES=50;52;60;70;80`.
- The option is passed through as `onnxruntime_PARALLEL` without making any assumptions (e.g. `parallel=0 == os.cpu_count()`) to make it reusable for other EPs down the line.

title: [WIP] ORTModule memory refinement
body:
**Description**:  memory refinement

On a simplified models constructed by stacking autograd.Function instances. So most of computations runs on PyTorch kernels, this is a good baseline to compare PyTorch with ORT. From memory profiling, we see ORT takes 16% more memory than PyTorch runs, obviously there are some bugs. 

ORTModuleFunction holds all the calculated gradients until backward completed, BUT Pytorch will accumulate the calculated gradients into param.grad immediately once gradient computations comes to any of the leaf node (AccumulateGrad function). 

The commit (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/8979/commits/29eebc29571678d13258e11bc43c09ad7201fa09) in this PR, tries to 1). use similar idea of https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/8993 (cut off the connection between ORTModuleFunction and its inputs' AccumulateGrad gradient function. then PyTorch will not not accumulate the ORTModuleFunction backward outputs into param.grad. 2). we do the gradient in-place update (into param.grad) on the ONNX graph.
  
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10530022/132364768-81f4d607-18f1-4dbf-8dca-1a0ee2340c71.png)

Description: custom autograd func memory refinement

In PythonOp glue code, we run the PyTorch code using torch tensor (constructed from the upstream ORTValue), this torch tensor is a leaf node when constructed with DLPack. So during forward function runs, there are edges connected to the leaf tensor, which will have a AccumulateGrad gradient function. Having AccumulateGrad gradient function reference the leaf variable , so that means, until AccumulateGrad gradient function is destroyed after PythonOpGrad completed and calls unregister_grad_fn, then the leaf variable will be released. This increase the life time of the variable a lot.

The changes in this PR is, after THPFunction_apply completed, we cut off the edge connection to the leaf variable, then the AccumulateGrad gradient function will be release immediately.

title: Only wrap sub-modules which can be wrapped as ORTModule
body:
Some `nn.Module`s are not exportable to ONNX. In those cases, we provide another class which only delegates supported computation to `ORTModule`. Let's consider an example.

```python
class A(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(A, self).__init__()
        self.l1 = nn.Linear(2, 2)
    def forward(self, x):
        return self.l1(x)

# This module is not exportable to ONNX because it
# uses gradient-checkpointing.
class B(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(B, self).__init__()
        self.l1 = nn.Linear(2, 2)
        self.a = A()
    def forward(self, x):
        def custom():
            def custom_forward(x_):
                return self.a(x_)
            return custom_forward
        z = self.l1(checkpoint(custom(), x))
        return z

# A supported module.
class C(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(C, self).__init__()
        self.l1 = nn.Linear(2, 2)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = F.relu(self.l1(x))
        return y

# This module is not exportable to ONNX because it
# inner module self.b uses gradient-checkpointing.
class D(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(D, self).__init__()
        self.b = B()

    def forward(self, x):
        y = F.sigmoid(self.b(x))
        return y

# Main module.
class Main(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(Main, self).__init__()
        self.alpha = nn.Parameter(torch.tensor(0.941736), requires_grad=True)
        self.a = A()
        self.b = B()
        self.c = C()
        self.d = D()

    def forward(self, x):
        z = self.alpha * self.d(self.c(self.b(self.a(x))))
        return z
```
Here the `Main` module consists of exportable and non-exportable sub-modules. To accelerate its computation, with this PR, we can do
```python
x = torch.rand(2).requires_grad_()
m = Main()
m = HierarchalORTModule(m)
t = m(x,)
t.sum().backward()

# Model after wrapping:
# a ORTModule()
# b B(
#   (l1): ORTModule()
#   (a): ORTModule()
# )
# c ORTModule()
# d D(
#   (b): B(
#     (l1): ORTModule()
#     (a): ORTModule()
#   )
# )
```
With proper use of `PythonOp`, this PR enables efficient activation-checkpointing in GPT-2.

title: Disable FastGelu Half2 Kernel by default
body:
**Description**:

FastGelu is widely used in GPT-2 model.  Its half2 kernel has negative impact on accuracy (top 1 mis-match rate 1.6% => 1.9%). Disable it by default. The impact on performance is small (< 0.1ms) for  GPT-2 model with 12 layer 768 hidden.

Option | average_latency (ms) | diff_50_percentile | diff_90_percentile | diff_95_percentile | diff_99_percentile | top1_match_rate
-- | -- | -- | -- | -- | -- | --
Baseline | 7.50 | 0.36256 | 1.2940 | 1.92666 | 5.23579 | 0.981
Disable Half2 | 7.58 | 0.36424 | 1.3632 | 1.99048 | 5.27358 | 0.984

The above test results are from T4 GPU like the following:
```
export ORT_CUDA_GEMM_OPTIONS=0
python gpt2_parity.py -m gpt2 --csv gpt2_parity.csv --runs 5 --use_gpu

export ORT_TRANSFORMER_OPTIONS=4
python gpt2_parity.py -m gpt2 --csv gpt2_parity.csv --runs 5 --use_gpu
```
**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

Some GPT-2 fp16 model has precision lost. It seems that one cause is the half2 kernel used in FastGelu. There are two solutions: disable half2 or use fp32 FastGelu. The second solution will have larger latency so we prefer to disable half2 kernel by default.

title: Revert "disable half2 kernel by default (#9034)"
body:
**Description**: This reverts commit 289999af351e3fea1568c2f8b97b9d3847f3ce82.

Previously, we disabled the half2 kernel based on experiments that it has negative impact on GPT-2 top 1 match rate. Later, we added [U-Test](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test) and [T-Test](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test) in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/9042, and the result shows that the difference is not significant. For example, 30 runs (each run has 1000 samples) have p_value=0.1484 in T-Test and p_value=0.1965 in U-Test. Usually, we need p_value < 0.05 to tell that two results have significant difference.

So we undo the change and keep half2 kernel since it has benefit on performance.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Implement better past state parsing semantics for language models
body:
TODO: Tests + Contrib CPU kernels for the 2 contrib ops

**Description**: 

Decoders in language models require parsing a "past state" (which is a sequence of tensors in some models) as the first order of business. Currently, this step is too compute-heavy for the simple operation it is trying to perform: parse tensors from a sequence and pass each tensor for downstream processing.

This is the existing logic for past state parsing. 

On the very first iteration, when there is no "past state", a past state seed is used is used and repeated `N` times to form the initial past state. This subgraph looks like this (a `SequenceInsert` running in a `Loop` in an `If` else subgraph):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/133527473-92dae039-2b92-4323-b542-3a61333312a3.png)
  
Loop subgraph:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/133527496-b3802ca0-909d-42fb-82f2-31fb28fe6039.png)
  
This Loop is too heavy as `SequenceInsert` needs to copy its input contents and then insert a tensor into the sequence on every iteration.

On the remaining iterations:

The past state sequence passes through an `Identity`  (in an `If` then subgraph). This Identity cannot be eliminated as it consumes a subgraph input and produces a subgraph output.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/133527686-2e1259c5-0989-496b-ae80-d64ff470f7a0.png)

This Identity makes a copy of the input sequence.

Once the past state is finalized, it is "parsed" using an array of `SequenceAt`(s)

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/133527869-edf7278c-0f16-4b8e-ab38-f8034a950514.png)

Each `SequenceAt` will need to make a copy of the tensor it is parsing.

This is the proposed semantics:

One operator outside the Loop to construct the "initial" past state (avoids the `SequenceInsert` in a `Loop`):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/133528153-0be33d43-08d9-4949-be10-9f6140ce3eda.png)

 
Another operation within the `Loop` to parse tensors from the sequence (avoids the `Identity`).  In addition to this, this operation will remove the array of `SequenceAt`(s) because it will produce the parsed tensors directly:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/133528697-99992eae-1776-42d0-80e3-e7a907c3c09e.png)

Furthermore, this change proposes extending the static allocation planner's `Aliasing` functionality to tensor sequences such that a tensor in the input sequence can be aliased as an output tensor in the parsing operator if other aliasing criteria are met. 

The proposed set of operations saves all the copies in the Loop due to past state parsing. 

**Motivation and Context**
10-15% perf boost for  1P model and scales to other language models using a similar approach of past state parsing.

The copy savings are proportional to both the number of elements in the past state sequence and the number of Loop iterations.
